sec.p:
We used brain areas which had significantly disrupted FC with NAc as potential features and examined their ability to discriminate patients with recurrent MDDs from healthy controls by using a support vector machine (SVM) in Matlab. SVM could handle data in a high-dimensional space and create a hyperplane that could best classify a new target into predefined categories. A Grid search method was used to obtain optimal values of hyperparameters (such as parameter C and Gamma) of a model. A fivefold cross-validation method was employed to assess the generalizability of classifier models. We trained those models with a Gaussian kernel in 80% of participants and evaluated the models’ performance on the left-out data in the “testing phase” for each fold. This method is good at handling high-dimensional data with optimal boundaries constructed and misclassification error minimized and is less likely to overfitting of the data [38, 39]. Finally, accuracy was calculated based on the results of cross-validation:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
